P.Span: Using a combination of SAS Viya with Open-Source simulating pool and knock-out fixtures at the Rugby World Cup in France 2023.
The model starts by using 18 months of international fixture results to estimate a team's win rate.
The simulation model then simulates win probabilities for each side, the side with the higher probability wins the fixture.
Over 20,000 simulations the model begins to converge on tournament favourites.
This dashboard showcases the simulations using a combination of path analyses and summary statistics.
I hope to re-run the simulations and update the dashboard as the tournament progresses!
Last refreshed 01/09/2023
Win Rate Probability Model

Bayesian models are a flexible form of statistical model where learned parameters are random variables with the form p(beta|y) = p(beta)p(y|beta). This allows the model to continually update beliefs with information.

In this project we use a hierarchical Bayesian model to estimate the distribution for win rate. Hierarchical models use shared parameters instead of constant priors. This allows the model to learn interdependencies between levels. In this model it is assumed that each team's win rate comes from a common population parameter for win rate. Given that we are modelling sparse data here. The inputs for the model are the win rates and the model output is a Bernoulli variable. We learn the parameter estimate of Beta, which is the probability of a win for the Bernoulli variable. This is updated by the actual observations we have.

Shown by the DAG to the right, we can see that the Bernoulli variable is learned at the match level whilst the Beta variable is learned at the team level. This allows us to estimate team level win rates by taking into account which teams typically beat which other teams. This is important because a win against South Africa is more meaningful than a win against a side like Italy in estimating a teams strength and propensity to win matches.
Estimated Win Rates
The output of the Bayesian model is distributional in nature. We draw 60,000 random samples from the posterior distribution to estimate the true distribution of win rate for any given side.

Sides where we have little information or inconsistent performance will have wider ranges of possible values. Sides which are in a period of high performance will have consistently higher estimates for win rate.

The chart to the right shows the estimated ranges for win rate. Sides such as France, South Africa and New Zealand have narrow intervals and relatively high win rates. These are the on-form sides and bookmakers favourites to win the World Cup.
Sides such as Canada, Hong Kong and Portugal have very wide parameter estimates as there are not many observations available and they rarely play Tier 1 nations.

Span.Span: This uncertainty does mean that Tier 2 sides are often overestimated for performance in the simulation model as we are not very confident on what the

P.Span: underlying ability of these teams are. This is why we run the simulations many times to get an estimate of the most likely occurences.

P.Span: The Simulation Model

Since the data is very sparse, with many sides in the tournament having not played others in recent years it is not possible to estimate fixture level results directly. For example, the dataset contains only 1 observation for Portugal who played Italy in 2022. We therefore simulate fixtures by randomly sampling a win rate from the posterior distributions from the probability model. A sample is taken for each side in the fixture, and the side more likely to win is the winner.

Whilst this is crude, over many simulations distinct patterns begin to emerge. Do Portugal ever win the World Cup? Maybe a handful of times because we have such a wide distribution of win rates for them but on average teams with narrower distributions will have a higher win rate.
The simulation model itslelf is just a Python function which iterates 20,000 times and uploads the results into CAS directly

P.Span: Are Portugal really more likely than England to reach the Knock-Out Stages?

Looking at the Path Comparison tab it is easy to assume that Portugal are more likely to reach the Quarter-Finals than England. In 2019 England reached the Final of the Rugby World Cup in Tokyo, whereas Portugal did not even qualify to play in the last tournament. So why is it that the simulation model has them as preferred winners of Quarter Final 3, which is the scenario where the winner of Pool D plays the runner-up of Pool C.

Firstly, England are in Pool D which has Argentina as favourites to win the pool. Thus it is more likely that England play in Quarter Final 1 as runners-up of Pool D. Secondly, the dataset contains exactly one result for Portugal where they played Italy in 2022. The sparsity of the data leads to great uncertainty on team parity.

Even a strong Tier 2 side, like Georgia who many believe should feature in the Six Nations, have only four observations. In fact, if we only consider teams ranked outside the IRB Top 10 the sum of all observations (17) is far less than the number of observations of top sides like Argentina. Only Fiji and Japan (who rank in the top 10) have fewer than 17 observations in the dataset. It is also worth noting that the quality of fixtures may not be the same for Tier 2 sides. The Six Nations and The Championship feature the top Northern and Southern hemisphere sides so the observations from those fixtures are well matched and against the top sides.
